===Etymology 2===
{{rfv|ja|An Okinawan word. It's "obsolete" and "Okinawan" (i.e. it's not Japanese), so doesn't that make it not suitable for a Japanese entry?}}
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|ぐすく}}

[[Appendix:Glossary#loanword|Borrowed]] from older {{bor|ja|ryu|sort=くすく'|-}} (Modern {{cog|ryu||城|tr=gushiku}}). The final ''ku'' may be cognate with mainland Japanese ''ki'' (see below).

The initial ''gu'' may be cognate with {{m|ja|御|tr=go||honorific}}, but it is problematic in that the only honorary prefixes found in [[w:Omoro Sōshi|Omoro Sōshi]] are {{m|ja|御|tr=mi}} and {{m|ja|御|tr=o}}. ''Suku'' may be related to {{m|ja|しけ|tr=shike||a holy place}} or cognate with {{m|ja|塞|tr=soko||fortress}}. While written with the kanji for "castle", textual and cultural evidence suggests that the initial primary meaning was a holy place.

